This weekend they are getting some help from an unlikely source : Nickelodeon, the No. 1 network for children, is replacing its usual Saturday afternoon lineup with a message encouraging young viewers to go outside and play. High-profile reports have linked television watching to childhood obesity, for example. That has left children's networks -- including the No. 2 player -- Cartoon Network -- with a tricky balancing act. Marva Smalls, executive vice president for public affairs at Nickelodeon, acknowledged that awareness about childhood obesity is up, but said the network's initiatives were not a response to outside pressure. 